Name Class Diagram1

Summary
 
Name Documentation
CMessageSystem

Description:

  The Message System has a queue of BaseMessage* and sends received messages to a MessageProc that will be on GameplayState. Its main functionality is for destruction and creation of objects.

Stipulations: 

  SendMsg() function is called every time an object wants to send a message to the MessageProc. ProcessMessages() should be called every frame in GameplayState.

Interface

  This class needs access to the CBaseMessage interface since it has a vector of pointers to it.

CBaseMessage

Description:

  Base class for messages that has a message ID. Every customized message created in the game will inherit from this class.

Stipulations: 

  This class is used by MessageSystem, that holds a queue of BaseMessage*. Every object that creates and sends messages will also have to know about it.

Interface

  This class doesn't need access to anything else.

CObjectManager

Description:

  The Object Manager class has a vector of IBaseInterface* and actually holds all the game objects, items and characters in it.

Stipulations: 

  When the RenderObjects() function is called, ObjectManager is responsible for calling Render() in all the objects of its vector. When the UpdateObjects() function is called, ObjectManager is responsible for calling Update() in all the objects of its vector. AddObject(), RemoveObject() and RemoveAllObjects() are functions used by GameplayState to access the vector of objects ObjectManager holds.

Interface

  This module needs access to IBaseInterface, since it has a vector of it.

IBaseInterface

Description:

  This is an abstract base class with pure virtual functions from which all characters and objects in the game inherit from.

Stipulations: 

  This class main purpose is for Object Manager to be able to store all game objects, items and characters in a vector of IBaseInterface*

Interface

  This module is dependant on AnimationManager since it hold two animation IDs for every object that inherit from it: a Move animation and a Destroy animation.

CPickUp

Description:

  This pickup has the default information for the few types of pickups that drop from enemies or pops out of breakable objects. It has a function to handle spawning the pickup and another to handle when the pickup is grabbed by the player.

Stipulations: 

  There's no limit on how many instances you can have of this class. CGamePlayState spawns them when a specific message is received and the player picks them up when collides with them.

Interface

  Does not have knowledge of any other modules (although the player has knowledge of this)

CProjectile

Description:
  This module will create a brand new Projectile. It can be of a different Type to differentiate itself from others created. It has an initialize function to give the projectile a starting position of x and y. It also has a damage counter to attack either a player or enemy. An animation would be attached to each projectile along with a RECT to determine collision. Render and Shutdown are handled to draw and delete the projectile when it has done its job.
Stipulations:
  This class can be instantiated in any class that needs it. It will also have a connection with particle manager to create particles where it needs to be. It inherets from IBaseInterface.
Interface:
  IBaseInterface functinality with a void* and owner to determine whom is shooting it.

CAnimationPlayer

Description:

  This module contains the current state of each animation to play.

Stipulations:

  The AnimationPlayer class contains an animation ID, a duration, a frame number and a timer. It has the Play(), Stop(), Reset() and Update() functions.

Interface:

  This module will be dependant on AnimationManager.

CAnimationManager

Description:

  This module manages the animations. You will load your animations to this class and receive an int to its location in the vector. This class is a singleton because we would never want multiple versions creating animations.

Stipulations:

  There can only ever be one instance of the AnimationManager. This class will hold a vector of Animations and will contain Load(), Unload() and UnloadAll() functions.

Interface:

  This module will access Frame and Animation. AnimationPlayer requires this class to function.

CAnimation

Description:

  This module contains all data for animations. It contains a vector of Frames, an ID and bools containing information about the animation style (IsLooping, IsPlaying, IsOscillating).

Stipulations:

  This class holds all of the data needed to make an Animation. This information will be loaded from an XML file exported by the Animation Editor.

Interface:

  This module will access Frame. AnimationManager requires this class to function.

CEventSystem

Description:

  The EventSystem class has a multimap of IListener* and strings (Event IDs) and a list of Events. This class will receive fired events and send them to the listeners who subscribed for that specific event, thus allowing more interaction between the game classes.

Stipulations: 

  SendEvent() function will send an event with a specific string as its ID to all classes that inherit from IListener and called RegisterForEvent() function, subscribing for that specific event. To do that, ProcessEvents() needs to be called every frame.

Interface

  This module needs access to Event and IListener, since it has the stored as data members.

CInputManager

Description:

  This module manages the games input. It will return the keys pressed to the player. This class is a singleton because we would never want multiple versions getting the input. It will contain both Keyboard and Controller input.

Stipulations: 

  There can only ever be one instance of the CInputManager class.  This will be the only class to get input.

Interface:

  This module will access xinput and directinput. 

CFrame

Description:

  This module contains a DrawRect, CollisionRect, AnchorPoint, Duration and an Event string. This is the  base unit every animation is made of.

Stipulations:

  This class contains all the data needed for an Animation frame. Many of these will be held by the Animation class in a vector.

Interface:

  The Frame class doesn't need access to anything else, but Animation requires access to this class to function.

CEvent

Description:

  The Event class handles the information of a single event: a string ID and a pointer to a parameter that can be anything.

Stipulations: 

  It's used by most of the functions in the EventSystem.

Interface

  This module doesn't need access to anything.

IListener

Description:

  The IListener class is a Base Interface for classes that care about events to inherit from.

Stipulations: 

  Every class that wants to perform an action when a certain event is sent needs to inherit from IListener and overwrite the HandleEvent() function.

Interface

  This module depends on an Event that is sent as a parameter to the HandleEvent() function.

CPlayer

Description
  The player has the actions of a 4-way top-down controllable fighter. Player can attack, charge up an attack, get hurt, die, level up, and do random callouts when killing enemies.
Stipulations
  Only one player. Gameplaystate creates and has the player. Player sends messages to perform actions.
Interface
  Gameplaystate knows the player. Player knows the Input module, Render module, Particle module. Affects gameplaystate depending on actions (dies, or enters new place).

IBaseCharacter

Description:

  This is an abstract base class with pure virtual functions from which all characters (Player, Enemies and NPCs) inherit from. It inherits from IBaseInterface.

Stipulations: 

  When a character is created, Initialize() should be called to set all of this character's variables. All the other functions are called by Object Manager when updating/rendering/checking collisions with all objects managed by it.

Interface

  This module needs access to IBaseInterface, since it inherits from it. It also inherits from IListener, since it has a HandleState function.

CPuzzleManager

Description:

  The Puzzle Manager class handles all puzzles of the game, storing pointers to all of them and calling update in all of them for every frame.

Stipulations:

  There should only be one instance of the Puzzle Manager, so it's a singleton. It's Puzzles vector is filled in by the GameplayState's CreatePuzzles() function.

Interface:

  This module will need to access CPuzzle.

CNPC

Description:

  This is a class that handles the behavior of a simple NPC. It inherits from IBaseCharacter and has a text string that is displayed when the player gets close to him and presses the action button.

Stipulations: 

  The Update() function will check for user input and check if the player is near the NPC. Render() will render the NPC and, if the Talk bool is true, render text to the screen.

Interface

  This module will need access to IBaseCharacter, since it inherits from it.

CPuzzle

Description:

  The Puzzle class is a generic class that holds a n number of ints, a string for an event and two function pointers. This class served for the organization of sequential puzzles that require some kind of generic interaction.

Stipulations:

  When the programmer creates a puzzle, he'll have to set a number of arguments this puzzle will need to keep track of, a string for the event the puzzle will be waiting for, and two function pointers that will define the behavior of the puzzle when receiving the event it's waiting and when updating every frame.

  For example, let's suppose our game has a puzzle in which the player has to light 4 torches in a certain order ( 1 to 4) to open a door. When the player lights a torch throughout collision/input, an event "TorchLit" will be sent with the torch ID as a parameter. When creating my Puzzle object, I make sure to set its event string to "TorchLit" and its argument count to 4, since I'll have to keep track of 4 torches (in this case, every int will actually behave as a bool). I then create a function that will check the event's parameter to know which torch was just lit, and if all the arguments for the torches that should come before of this one are true, I should set this one to true also. If not, I should reset all the torches. I send this function to the Puzzle as the handleEvent function pointer. Finally, I create a function that checks if all 4 arguments are true, and if they are, I send an event called "OpenDoor" and reset the torches. I send this function to the Puzzle as the Update function pointer. Now, my puzzle will check the order and change its variables every time a torch is lit, and when the 4 torches are lit in the right sequence, a door will open.

Interface:

  This module will need access to the Event system.

CBaseEnemy

Description:

  This is a base enemy class that handles basic behavior for any enemy on the game.

Stipulations: 

  When an enemy is created, Initialize() should be called. ChangeAIState() should be used to switch from an AI State to other. This AI State defines how the enemy should behave. Its functions are called in Update() and Render().

Interface

  This module needs access to CBaseCharacter, since it inherits from it. It needs access to IBaseAIState, since it has an AI State pointer to handle AI.

CTileset

Description:

  The Tileset class handles all the information that defines a tileset: an imageID that is loaded in memory by TextureManager, the width and height of every single tile, in pixels, and the width and height of the whole tileset, in number of tiles.

Stipulations: 

  Tilesets are going to be created by GameplayState in heap memory and will be passed as pointers to every Map that could use them. They handle information needed to render the map to the screen.

Interface:

  This module won't need direct access to any other class.

CTile

Description:

  The Tile class has the information needed to get the right drawing rectangle from a Tileset for a specific tile. It also has an ID representing its type that is used for puzzles and collision checks.

Stipulations:

  The Tile class is used as a structure to hold Layer's data, since it has a vector of Tiles, filled in by Map's Load() function, in which Tiles are created and stored in memory.

Interface:

  This module won't need direct access to any other class.

CMap

Description:

  The Map class has all the data and functions needed to load a complete map from an XML file, storing its Width, Height and all Tiles and Layers. It also has a pointer to a Tileset allocated outside of this class and a Position in the World, which is set on the Initialize function.

Stipulations: 

  To create a Map in the World, the programmer will have to create a Map object, call Initialize() sending the XML file to be loaded, a pointer to the Tileset to be used and the position of this map relative to the World origin. Render() will loop through every Layer, then through every Tile for each Layer and render all of them. Shutdown() should only be called when the program exits.

Interface

  This class needs access to Tileset since it uses the data of one for everything it renders and also needs access to Layer since it stores all the loaded information in them and gets the Tiles' specific render information from them.

CGameplayState

Description:
  The CGameplayState class will handle all gameplay data and behavior. The game itself will be only playable through this state.
Stipulations:
  There can only ever be one instance of the CGameplayState class, so it should be a singleton.
Interface:
  This module will need to access IGameState since it inherits from it and will be require to overwrite all its functions and MainMenuState since the player will be redirected back to main menu if he exits this state. It will also be dependent on Object Manager and Player classes.

CLayer

Description:

  The Layer class has a vector of Tiles and is used to draw the map. The ID variable tells the Map object that contains it if this should be rendered below or above other existing layers.

Stipulations: 

  The Layer class has a vector of Tiles and all functions necessary to manipulate it(PushTile, PopTile, Clear and GetSize). It's used by Map to hold the Tiles loaded in memory and also to render them correctly.

Interface:

  The Layer class needs access to Tile, since it has a vector of it.

IBaseAIState

Description:

  This is an abstract base class that all other AI States will inherit from. The enemies' behavior will be handled by the overloaded functions in each state.

Stipulations: 

  When entering the state, Enter() should be called to initialize the variables, and thus Exit() should be called to shut it down. Render() and Update() are called every frame and can have really different implementations depending on the state they're in.

Interface

  This module doesn't need access to any other class.

CRandomAIState

Description:

  The Random AI State identifies a state in which the enemy will move randomly throughout the game world.

Stipulations: 

  When entering the state, Enter() should be called to initialize the variables, and thus Exit() should be called to shut it down. Render() and Update() are called every frame and in this case will just make sure that the enemy will get new random directions every x seconds.

Interface

  This module needs access to IBaseAIState since it inherits from it.

CIdleAIState

Description:

  The Idle AI State identifies a state in which the enemy won't move at all.

Stipulations: 

  When entering the state, Enter() should be called to initialize the variables, and thus Exit() should be called to shut it down. Render() and Update() are called every frame and in this case will just make sure that the enemy doesn't move until the player comes closer.

Interface

  This module needs access to IBaseAIState since it inherits from it.

Emitter

Description:

  This module creates many instances of the Particle class.  It manages many other important facets by creating the Particle, setting their positions, durations, etc.  It can change the color of the Particles texture and even blend them together to give it a nice effect.  Rotation and be changed and so can Scale.  Point Gravity and normal gravity can be applied to give the particles cooler effects.

Stipulations:

  This class can be made instances of many different times with many different modes.  You can call as many as there is enough memory to allow.

Interface:

  It will have access to DirectX functionality

Particle

Description:

This Module contains the actual Particle.  It only has data members to describe what a particle is.

Stipulations:

There can be several thousand Particles on the screen at any given time.  The Emitter class is responsible for creating new particles.

Interface:

This module will have no access to any class.  It can be a struct or a class.

CSwarmAIState

Description:

  The Swarm AI State identifies a state in which the enemy will look for the player and follow him.

Stipulations: 

  When entering the state, Enter() should be called to initialize the variables, and thus Exit() should be called to shut it down. Render() and Update() are called every frame and in this case will just make sure that the enemy will always be moving towards the player.

Interface

  This module needs access to IBaseAIState since it inherits from it.

CMainMenuState

Description:
  The CMainMenuState class will give the player the ability to go to either the game, the options menu or the credits menu.
Stipulations:
  There can only ever be one instance of the CMainMenuState class, so it should be a singleton.
Interface:
  This module will need to access IGameState since it inherits from it and will be require to overwrite all its functions. It will also need access to GameplayState, OptionsState and CreditsState, since it will redirect the player to any one of those.

COptionsState

Description:
  The COptionsState class will display the game options and allow the player to choose audio and controller settings.
Stipulations:
  There can only ever be one instance of the COptionsState class, so it should be a singleton.
Interface:
  This module will need to access IGameState since it inherits from it and will be require to overwrite all its functions and MainMenuState since the player will be redirected back to main menu if he exits this state.

ParticleManager

Description:
  This module runs every emitter. It creates a vector of Emitters that update and render onto the screen. A data structure is used to store and unload every emitter to add and clean up memory during runtime to keep from swiss cheesing our code.
  Stipulations:
There is only one instance of the particle manager. CGamePlayState will create and handgle everything that has to do with Particle manager. This instance will need to be deleted when the window closes.
Interface:
  This module will be used in most game modules because there is a need to create a particle everywhere on screen from MainMenu to Game, to Ending Credits.

IGameState

Description:
  IGameState is a pure virtual base class to that all other game states inherit from. It contains all the functions that are required by a State.
Stipulations:
  All game states will be classes inheriting from IGameState and all of them need to overwrite the Enter(), Input(), Update(), Render() and Exit() functions.
Interface:
    This module won't need direct access to any other class.

CameraControl

Description:
This module will create a brand new camera that can be positioned anywhere the programmer wishes to use it. It also has functionality to set itself to any ingame object by calling its set methods and inputting positions. The Update will reposition the camera every frame. There is also functionality to allow the camera to change its Y vector to zoom in on any location for however long the programmer wishes.
Stipulations:
This class is a SingleTon. It can be accessed anywhere and manipulated at any spot.
Interface:
It will have acess to DirectX functionality and have easy to access methods with simple parameters to dramatically change the camera to the programmers choosing.

CCreditsState

Description:
  The CCreditsState class will display the game credits scrolling up.
Stipulations:
  There can only ever be one instance of the CCreditsState class, so it should be a singleton.
Interface:
  This module will need to access IGameState since it inherits from it and will be require to overwrite all its functions and MainMenuState since the player will be redirected back to main menu if he exits this state.

Stipulations: 

  SendMsg() function is called every time an object wants to send a message to the MessageProc. ProcessMessages() should be called every frame in GameplayState.

Interface

  This class needs access to the CBaseMessage interface since it has a vector of pointers to it.

Documentation

Description:

  The Object Manager class has a vector of IBaseInterface* and actually holds all the game objects, items and characters in it.

Stipulations: 

  When the RenderObjects() function is called, ObjectManager is responsible for calling Render() in all the objects of its vector. When the UpdateObjects() function is called, ObjectManager is responsible for calling Update() in all the objects of its vector. AddObject(), RemoveObject() and RemoveAllObjects() are functions used by GameplayState to access the vector of objects ObjectManager holds.

Interface

  This module needs access to IBaseInterface, since it has a vector of it.

Interface

  This module is dependant on AnimationManager since it hold two animation IDs for every object that inherit from it: a Move animation and a Destroy animation.

  This pickup has the default information for the few types of pickups that drop from enemies or pops out of breakable objects. It has a function to handle spawning the pickup and another to handle when the pickup is grabbed by the player.

Stipulations:

Interface

  Does not have knowledge of any other modules (although the player has knowledge of this)

Documentation

Description:
  This module will create a brand new Projectile. It can be of a different Type to differentiate itself from others created. It has an initialize function to give the projectile a starting position of x and y. It also has a damage counter to attack either a player or enemy. An animation would be attached to each projectile along with a RECT to determine collision. Render and Shutdown are handled to draw and delete the projectile when it has done its job.
Stipulations:
  This class can be instantiated in any class that needs it. It will also have a connection with particle manager to create particles where it needs to be. It inherets from IBaseInterface.
Interface:
  IBaseInterface functinality with a void* and owner to determine whom is shooting it.

Description:

  This module manages the animations. You will load your animations to this class and receive an int to its location in the vector. This class is a singleton because we would never want multiple versions creating animations.

Stipulations:

  There can only ever be one instance of the AnimationManager. This class will hold a vector of Animations and will contain Load(), Unload() and UnloadAll() functions.

Interface:

  This module will access Frame and Animation. AnimationPlayer requires this class to function.

Documentation

Description:

  The EventSystem class has a multimap of IListener* and strings (Event IDs) and a list of Events. This class will receive fired events and send them to the listeners who subscribed for that specific event, thus allowing more interaction between the game classes.

Stipulations: 

  SendEvent() function will send an event with a specific string as its ID to all classes that inherit from IListener and called RegisterForEvent() function, subscribing for that specific event. To do that, ProcessEvents() needs to be called every frame.

Interface

  This module needs access to Event and IListener, since it has the stored as data members.

Name does not contain glossary terms Define name as term in glossary
Documentation

Description:

  This is an abstract base class with pure virtual functions from which all characters (Player, Enemies and NPCs) inherit from. It inherits from IBaseInterface.

Stipulations: 

  When a character is created, Initialize() should be called to set all of this character's variables. All the other functions are called by Object Manager when updating/rendering/checking collisions with all objects managed by it.

Interface

  This module needs access to IBaseInterface, since it inherits from it. It also inherits from IListener, since it has a HandleState function.

Documentation

Description:

  The Puzzle Manager class handles all puzzles of the game, storing pointers to all of them and calling update in all of them for every frame.

Stipulations:

  There should only be one instance of the Puzzle Manager, so it's a singleton. It's Puzzles vector is filled in by the GameplayState's CreatePuzzles() function.

Interface:

  This module will need to access CPuzzle.

Description:

  The Puzzle class is a generic class that holds a n number of ints, a string for an event and two function pointers. This class served for the organization of sequential puzzles that require some kind of generic interaction.

Stipulations:

  When the programmer creates a puzzle, he'll have to set a number of arguments this puzzle will need to keep track of, a string for the event the puzzle will be waiting for, and two function pointers that will define the behavior of the puzzle when receiving the event it's waiting and when updating every frame.

  For example, let's suppose our game has a puzzle in which the player has to light 4 torches in a certain order ( 1 to 4) to open a door. When the player lights a torch throughout collision/input, an event "TorchLit" will be sent with the torch ID as a parameter. When creating my Puzzle object, I make sure to set its event string to "TorchLit" and its argument count to 4, since I'll have to keep track of 4 torches (in this case, every int will actually behave as a bool). I then create a function that will check the event's parameter to know which torch was just lit, and if all the arguments for the torches that should come before of this one are true, I should set this one to true also. If not, I should reset all the torches. I send this function to the Puzzle as the handleEvent function pointer. Finally, I create a function that checks if all 4 arguments are true, and if they are, I send an event called "OpenDoor" and reset the torches. I send this function to the Puzzle as the Update function pointer. Now, my puzzle will check the order and change its variables every time a torch is lit, and when the 4 torches are lit in the right sequence, a door will open.

Interface:

  This module will need access to the Event system.

Name does not contain glossary terms Define name as term in glossary
Documentation

Description:

  The Map class has all the data and functions needed to load a complete map from an XML file, storing its Width, Height and all Tiles and Layers. It also has a pointer to a Tileset allocated outside of this class and a Position in the World, which is set on the Initialize function.

Stipulations: 

  To create a Map in the World, the programmer will have to create a Map object, call Initialize() sending the XML file to be loaded, a pointer to the Tileset to be used and the position of this map relative to the World origin. Render() will loop through every Layer, then through every Tile for each Layer and render all of them. Shutdown() should only be called when the program exits.

Interface

  This class needs access to Tileset since it uses the data of one for everything it renders and also needs access to Layer since it stores all the loaded information in them and gets the Tiles' specific render information from them.

Documentation

Description:

  This is an abstract base class that all other AI States will inherit from. The enemies' behavior will be handled by the overloaded functions in each state.

Stipulations: 

  When entering the state, Enter() should be called to initialize the variables, and thus Exit() should be called to shut it down. Render() and Update() are called every frame and can have really different implementations depending on the state they're in.

Interface

  This module doesn't need access to any other class.
